<section xml:id="sec-differentiating-products-and-powers">
  <title>Differentiating products and powers</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Differentiate products by examining how each factor varies.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Justify and apply the Power Rule for natural-number exponents using differentials.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Combine linearity with product rules to differentiate polynomials.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Visual proof of Product Rule:
      </p>

      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\dd(u\cdot v) \amp = \dd{u} \cdot v + u \cdot \dd{v}</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = u\dd{v} + v\dd{u}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      
      <p>
        <me>
          \dv{x}(f(x)g(x))=f'(x) g(x)+f(x) g'(x)
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Apply to <m>x^{2}</m>:
        <me>
          \dd(x^{2})=x\dd{x} + x\dd{x} = 2x\dd{x}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Extend to three variables:
        <me>
          \dd(u\cdot v\cdot w)=\dd{u}\cdot v\cdot w+u\cdot \dd{v}\cdot w+u\cdot v\cdot \dd{w}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Apply to <m>x^{3}</m>:
        <me>
          \dd(x^{3})=\dd(x\cdot x\cdot x)=3x^{2}\dd{x}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Power Rule:
        <me>
          \dd(x^{n})=nx^{n-1}\dd{x}
        </me>
        (Only works when <m>n</m> is a natural number right now)
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Linearity properties:
      </p>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow>\dd(u+v) \amp = \dd{u}+\dd{v}</mrow>
          <mrow>\dd(cu) \amp = c\dd{u}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Derivative of a polynomial term by term
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

